{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = World Tales | image = World Tales (book cover).jpg | author = [[Idries Shah]] | cover_artist = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | publisher = Harcourt Brace Jovanovich, Octagon Press | release_date = December 25, 1979 | media_type = Print | pages = 410 | isbn = 0-86304-036-5 | isbn_note = (paperback) | oclc = 24743413 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''World Tales''''', subtitled "'''The Extraordinary Coincidence of Stories Told in All Times, in All Places'''" is a book of 65 [[Fairy tale|folk tales]] collected by [[Idries Shah]] from around the world, mostly from literary sources. Some of the tales are very current, others are less well known.
==Content== Each story is preceded by a short introduction by the author, giving a brief history of the tale's literary mutations, or remarking on the strange similarities that versions exhibit across great geographical or historical distances.<ref>For example, asking, with reference to the story of [[Childe Rowland]]: "How can it be that the same story is found in Scotland and also in pre-Columbian America?"</ref> The collection has had a broad appeal. For instance Canadian poet [[P. K. Page]] cited it as the book she would give to a child,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/writersandcompany/98readings.html|title=Home - Writers & Company with Eleanor Wachtel - CBC Radio|date=12 January 2016|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=2017-09-16}}</ref> and author and storyteller [[Norah Dooley]]:<ref name="NorahDolley">{{cite web | last = | first = | title = Norah Dooley ~ storyteller, author & activist | work = norahdooley.com | publisher = | date = 2012 | url = http://www.norahdooley.com/index.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161224001700/http://www.norahdooley.com/ | archive-date = 24 December 2016 | dead-url = yes | accessdate = 16 September 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://web.mac.com/dubhhero/iWeb/Norah%20Dooley/Welcome_files/MulticulturalStoriesforTeachersWithBibliog.pdf] {{dead link|date=September 2017}}</ref> "This is the book that turned my interest as an adult to folklore and inspired me to take up storytelling." and has become a widely used sourcebook of tales.<ref>{{cite book | last = O'Keefe | first = Ellen M. |author2=Stewart, Mary Catherine |author3=Senge, Peter M. | title = Tools for Conflict Resolution | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | year = 2004 | pages = 44 | isbn = 1-57886-110-1}}, {{cite book | last = Sherman | first = Josepha | title = Once Upon a Galaxy: Folktales, Fantasy, and Science Fiction | publisher = august house | year = 1994 | pages = 230 | isbn = 0-87483-387-6}} and {{cite book | last = Aldridge | first = David | title = Case Study Designs in Music Therapy | publisher = Jessica Kingsley Publishers | year = 2005 | pages = 29 | isbn = 1-84310-140-8}}</ref>
Whilst Shah mentions many of the ancient and modern interpretations that have been placed on the tales, along with some of the theories of [[Fairy tale#Cross-cultural transmission|cross-cultural transmission]], he himself interprets them little, writing in the introduction: {{cquote| Working for thirty-five years among the written and oral sources of our world heritage in tales, one feels a truly living element in them which is startlingly evident when one isolates the 'basic' stories: the ones which tend to have travelled furthest, to have featured in the largest number of classical collections, to have inspired great writers of the past and present.}} The value that Shah put on folklore of this kind is clear, not only from the many volumes of tales that he published but also from books published by his children. The title alone of one of his daughter [[Saira Shah]]'s books, ''The Storyteller's Daughter'',<ref>{{cite book | last = Shah | first = Saira | title = The Storyteller's Daughter | publisher = Penguin Books Ltd | year = 2004 | isbn = 0-14-101026-6 }} </ref> gives some indication, while his son [[Tahir Shah]]'s book ''[[In Arabian Nights]]'', itself an exploration of the power of the folktale, recalls:<ref>{{cite book | last = Shah | first = Tahir | title = In Arabian Nights | publisher = Random House Inc. | year = 2008 | pages = 13 | isbn = 978-0-553-80523-9}} </ref> {{cquote|When my father died a decade ago, I inherited his library. There were five reinforced boxes of books labeled "STORIES: VALUABLE, HANDLE WITH CARE". Among them were [[Aesop's Fables|Aesop's ''Fables'']], [[Hans Christian Andersen]], and the [[Brothers Grimm]]. There were many others too, the Arab collections and volumes of tales from every corner of the world... }}
==Original illustrated edition==
The book was first published in large format by [[Harcourt Brace Jovanovich]]<ref>{{cite book | last = Shah | first = Idries | title = World Tales | publisher = Harcourt Brace Jovanovich | year = 1979 | pages = 259 | isbn = 0-15-199434-X}} </ref> with each tale illustrated. Originally Shah asked [[Ivan Tyrrell]] to find illustrations for the tales by the likes of [[Arthur Rackham]], [[Kay Nielsen]] and [[Edmund Dulac]]. Tyrrell instead suggested commissioning new work, Shah agreed to this and the idea was put to, and approved by, the publisher, [[William Jovanovich]].<ref name="listening">{{cite book|last1=Tyrrell|first1=Ivan|title=Listening to Idries Shah|date=2016|publisher=Human Givens Publishing|isbn=978-1899398089|page=106}}</ref> Thirty seven artists<ref>David Aicken, Wayne Anderson, Philip Argent, [[Peter Brookes]], Fred Carver, Doranna, Roy Ellsworth, Brian Froud, Tim Gill, Peter Goodfellow, Melvyn Grant, Lynda Gray, Colin Hadley, Ivan Hissey, Ken Laidlaw, Roger Langton, Carol Lawson, Janina Lech, [[Alan Lee (illustrator)|Alan Lee]], James Marsh, Chris McEwan, Tony Meeuwissen, Martin Newton, David O'Connor, Joe Petagno, Sue Porter, Peter Richardson, Carolyn Scrace, Caroline Smith, Mike Terry, [[Alan Tunbridge]], [[Ivan Tyrrell]], George Underwood, Malcolm Walker, Mai Watts, Juan Wijngaard and Ray Winder</ref> contributed. This edition is no longer in print; the [[Octagon Press]] edition is text only.
Agnes Perkins, writing in the ''[[Children's Literature Association Quarterly]]'' cited this "lavish" edition of ''World Tales'' as an example of books that bridge the gap between illustrated books of folktales published for the juvenile market which pay little attention to sources or to authenticity of tone and language and which supply none of the working tools developed for folklore scholarship which might lead readers to further study of tales from the oral tradition, and collections by folklorists concerned primarily with local variants and the unusual persistence of motifs which ignore questions of the value of the stories from a literary standpoint.<ref>{{cite journal |author= Agnes Perkins|year= 1981|title= Folklore and Children's Books: Bridging the Gap|journal= [[Children's Literature Association Quarterly]] |volume= 6|issue= 2|pages= 1–37 |doi=10.1353/chq.0.1667}}</ref>
